Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
specifyCellEdgeSpacing(25.10)                    specifyCellEdgeSpacing(25.10)

Name
       specifyCellEdgeSpacing

Syntax
        specifyCellEdgeSpacing

       [-help]

       {<<edgeType1>> <<edgeType2>> <spacing>

       [-exceptExactSpacing   <distance>][-exceptAbutted   |   -forbiddenSpac-
       ing][-exceptNonFillerInBetween]} | [-reset]

       Creates the cell edge spacing rule as in CELLEDGESPACINGTABLE in LEF.

       The tool by default supports the latest Tcl settings. If a  user  tries
       to  change  the  edge spacing, the tool will generate a warning message
       that resetting edge spacing would overwrite the old value.

Parameters
       <-exceptAbutted>
              Specifies that two abutted macros of the given  edge  types  are
              also allowed.

       <edgeType1>
              Specifies edge edgeType1for edge spacing.

       <edgeType2>
              Specifies edge edgeType2 for edge spacing.

       -exceptExactSpacing <distance>
              Specifies an exception distance to the minimum spacing.

       -exceptNonFillerInBetween
              Specifies that the edge spacing is only for adjacent instances.

              If  two MACROs (cells) have a edge-spacing rule, say 0.8 micron,
              then normally the rule applies regardless of presence of another
              macro (cell) in the gap between. When the  -exceptNonFillerInBe-
              tween  option  is  used,  the rule is exempted when a non-filler
              cell is present between the two constrained cell edges.

       -forbiddenSpacing
              Forbids <edgeType1> and <edgeType2> with the space.

       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes type and  default  in-
              formation for each specifyCellEdgeSpacing parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command: man specifyCellEdgeSpacing

       -reset Resets the cell edge spacing to LEF.

       <spacing>
              Specifies edge spacing between <edgeType1> and <edgeType2>.

              If  there is no spacing defined between two edge types, it indi-
              cates that there is no spacing constraint (or 0.0 <micro>m)  be-
              tween them.

Example
       The  following  command  creates 0.18 <micro>m spacing between grp1 and
       grp2:

       specifyCellEdgeSpacing grp1 grp2 0.18

